%\label{sec:training}

%This section describes the training pipeline for DeXposure-FM, including data construction, multi-task objectives, and optimization. All graph and flow notation follows Section~\ref{sec:formalisation} (credit-exposure definition in Eq.~\eqref{eq:credit-exposure-definition}, node weights in Eq.~\eqref{eq:node-weight}, token-level flows in Eq.~\eqref{eq:value-flow}, and edge weights in Eq.~\eqref{eq:edge-weight}).

\subsection{Training Data Preparation}

For each discrete interval $\tau=t_2-t_1$ we construct a weighted directed snapshot $G_{\tau}=(\mathcal P_{\tau},\mathcal E_{\tau})$ with node weights $w_{\tau}(p)$ and edge weights $w_{\tau}(e_{pq})$. We form rolling training examples indexed by an anchor time $\tau$:
\begin{equation}
\underbrace{\{G_{\tau-L+1},\ldots,G_{\tau}\}}_{\text{context window}}
\;\longrightarrow\;
\underbrace{\{G_{\tau+1},\ldots,G_{\tau+H}\}}_{\text{forecast targets}},
\end{equation}
where $L$ is the context length and $H$ is the forecast horizon. For each protocol $p\in\mathcal P_{\tau}$ we also provide modality-specific inputs: a protocol-level time-series window $\mathbf x^{\mathrm{ts}}_{p,\tau-L+1:\tau}$, tabular protocol metadata $\mathbf x^{\mathrm{tab}}_{p}$, and the contemporaneous exposure graph $G_{\tau}$.

\paragraph{Time-based rolling splits.}
We evaluate models using time-based rolling splits (walk-forward validation), ensuring that all validation and test targets occur strictly after the corresponding training window to avoid look-ahead bias.

\paragraph{Scalable edge sampling.}
Since $|\mathcal E_{\tau}|$ can be large, we train with edge sampling. For each anchor $\tau$ and horizon $h$, we draw a set of positive edges from $\mathcal E_{\tau+h}$ with a mixture distribution that upweights large exposures (proportional to $w_{\tau+h}(e_{pq})$) while retaining a uniform component to preserve coverage of smaller links. When training an auxiliary link-existence head, we additionally sample non-edges as negatives.

\subsection{Training Pipeline}
This section describes the training pipeline.

\subsubsection{Training phases}
We use a three-phase training schedule to exploit pre-trained backbones while preventing catastrophic forgetting.

\paragraph{Phase A: adapter warm start (frozen backbones).}
We initialize the modality backbones (time-series, graph, tabular) from pre-trained checkpoints and freeze them. We train only lightweight adapters, fusion modules, the temporal core, and task heads until validation loss stabilizes.

\paragraph{Phase B: domain pretraining on DeXposure.}
We then pretrain on the full DeXposure history (excluding the final holdout block) using a mixture of masked reconstruction and predictive losses (Section~\ref{sec:training:loss}). Backbones may remain frozen, or be tuned via parameter-efficient methods (e.g., LoRA/adapters) with a smaller learning rate.

\paragraph{Phase C: task fine-tuning.}
Finally, we fine-tune on the benchmark tasks reported in the paper: (i) multi-step forecasting of edge and node weights and network statistics; (ii) scenario-conditioned stress paths; and (iii) imputation/denoising. We either fine-tune jointly with a weighted multi-task objective, or sequentially with early stopping if negative transfer is observed.

\subsubsection{Loss functions}
\label{sec:training:loss}
We train DeXposure-FM with a weighted multi-task objective that reflects heavy-tailed magnitudes and the economic importance of large exposures.

\paragraph{Edge forecasting loss}
We predict future edge weights $\widehat w_{\tau+h}(e_{pq})$ for horizons $h=1,\ldots,H$. Because exposures are heavy-tailed, we train in log space:
\begin{equation}
y_{\tau+h}(e_{pq}) = \log\bigl(1+w_{\tau+h}(e_{pq})\bigr),\qquad
\hat y_{\tau+h}(e_{pq}) = \log\bigl(1+\widehat w_{\tau+h}(e_{pq})\bigr).
\end{equation}
We use a robust regression loss (Huber / SmoothL1) with horizon weights $\omega_h$:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal L_{\mathrm{edge}}
=
\sum_{h=1}^{H}\omega_h\,
\mathbb E_{(p,q)\in \mathcal S_{\tau+h}}
\left[
\alpha_{pq,\tau+h}\;
\mathrm{Huber}\!\left(\hat y_{\tau+h}(e_{pq})-y_{\tau+h}(e_{pq})\right)
\right],
\label{eq:loss-edge}
\end{equation}
where $\mathcal S_{\tau+h}$ is the sampled edge set at horizon $h$. We set $\omega_h=\lambda^{h-1}$ with $\lambda\in(0,1]$ to mildly downweight longer horizons.

\paragraph{Economic-importance weighting.}
To prioritize economically material nodes and edges, we weight errors by
\begin{equation}
\alpha_{pq,\tau} =
\left(\log(1+w_{\tau}(p))\right)^{\eta}\,
\left(\log(1+w_{\tau}(e_{pq}))\right)^{1-\eta},
\label{eq:importance-weight}
\end{equation}
with $\eta\in[0,1]$, and clip $\alpha_{pq,\tau}$ to avoid domination by a handful of extreme edges.

\paragraph{Optional hurdle formulation (link + weight).}
To better handle sparsity, we optionally decompose forecasting into edge existence $a_{\tau+h}(p,q)\in\{0,1\}$ and a conditional weight. The existence head is trained with binary cross entropy:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal L_{\mathrm{link}}
=
\sum_{h=1}^{H}\omega_h\,
\mathbb E_{(p,q)\in \mathcal S_{\tau+h}}
\Bigl[\mathrm{BCE}\bigl(\hat a_{\tau+h}(p,q), a_{\tau+h}(p,q)\bigr)\Bigr],
\label{eq:loss-link}
\end{equation}
and $\mathcal L_{\mathrm{edge}}$ is applied only on positive edges.

\paragraph{Node forecasting loss}
We forecast node ``stock'' weights $\widehat w_{\tau+h}(p)$ (and/or related node signals). Using the same log transform,
\begin{equation}
\mathcal L_{\mathrm{node}}
=
\sum_{h=1}^{H}\omega_h\,
\mathbb E_{p\in \mathcal P_{\tau+h}}
\left[
\beta_{p,\tau+h}\;
\mathrm{Huber}\!\left(\log(1+\widehat w_{\tau+h}(p))-\log(1+w_{\tau+h}(p))\right)
\right],
\label{eq:loss-node}
\end{equation}
with $\beta_{p,\tau}=\log(1+w_{\tau}(p))$ (clipped) to emphasize large protocols.

\paragraph{Network statistics loss}
Let $\mathbf m_{\tau+h}$ denote a vector of network-level statistics (e.g., density, concentration, and sector connectivity). We train a pooled head $H_{\mathrm{net}}(\cdot)$ to predict these statistics and encourage consistency with the statistics implied by the predicted graph:
\begin{align}
\mathcal L_{\mathrm{stats}}
&=
\sum_{h=1}^{H}\omega_h\,
\left\|\widehat{\mathbf m}^{\mathrm{head}}_{\tau+h}-\mathbf m_{\tau+h}\right\|_2^2
+\lambda_{\mathrm{impl}}
\sum_{h=1}^{H}\omega_h\,
\left\|\widehat{\mathbf m}^{\mathrm{head}}_{\tau+h}-\widehat{\mathbf m}^{\mathrm{impl}}_{\tau+h}\right\|_2^2,
\label{eq:loss-stats}
\end{align}
where $\widehat{\mathbf m}^{\mathrm{impl}}_{\tau+h}=\Phi(\widehat G_{\tau+h})$ is computed deterministically from predicted edges and weights.

\paragraph{Masked reconstruction for imputation and denoising}
We pretrain and fine-tune with masked-modality objectives by masking a subset of time-series entries $\mathcal M_{\mathrm{ts}}$ and edge weights $\mathcal M_{\mathrm{edge}}$:
\begin{align}
\mathcal L_{\mathrm{impute,ts}}
&=
\mathbb E_{(p,t)\in\mathcal M_{\mathrm{ts}}}
\left[
\gamma_{p,t}\;
\mathrm{Huber}\!\left(\hat x^{\mathrm{ts}}_{p,t}-x^{\mathrm{ts}}_{p,t}\right)
\right],\\
\mathcal L_{\mathrm{impute,edge}}
&=
\mathbb E_{(p,q,\tau)\in\mathcal M_{\mathrm{edge}}}
\left[
\alpha_{pq,\tau}\;
\mathrm{Huber}\!\left(\hat y_{\tau}(e_{pq})-y_{\tau}(e_{pq})\right)
\right],\\
\mathcal L_{\mathrm{impute}}
&=\mathcal L_{\mathrm{impute,ts}}+\lambda_{\mathrm{impute,edge}}\,\mathcal L_{\mathrm{impute,edge}}.
\label{eq:loss-impute}
\end{align}
We report both reconstruction quality (including TVL-weighted errors) and downstream performance gains in forecasting and link prediction.

\paragraph{Scenario-conditioned stress loss and plausibility regularization}
For scenario analysis we condition the model on a structured shock vector $\mathbf c$ (e.g., stablecoin de-peg magnitude, collateral repricing, exchange outage indicator) and train conditional multi-step predictions. When historical stress windows are available, we supervise scenario paths with the same forecasting losses:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal L_{\mathrm{scen}}
=
\mathcal L_{\mathrm{edge}}(\mathbf c)
+\lambda_{\mathrm{node}}\mathcal L_{\mathrm{node}}(\mathbf c)
+\lambda_{\mathrm{stats}}\mathcal L_{\mathrm{stats}}(\mathbf c).
\label{eq:loss-scen}
\end{equation}
To improve scenario plausibility, we include a smoothness regularizer on predicted log-weights:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal L_{\mathrm{smooth}}
=
\sum_{h=2}^{H}
\mathbb E_{(p,q)\in\mathcal S_{\tau+h}}
\left|\hat y_{\tau+h}(e_{pq})-\hat y_{\tau+h-1}(e_{pq})\right|.
\label{eq:loss-smooth}
\end{equation}
Nonnegativity of predicted flows and exposures is enforced by the decoder (e.g., via \texttt{softplus}).

\paragraph{Overall objective}
The overall training objective is a weighted sum:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal L
=
\lambda_{\mathrm{edge}}\mathcal L_{\mathrm{edge}}
+\lambda_{\mathrm{link}}\mathcal L_{\mathrm{link}}
+\lambda_{\mathrm{node}}\mathcal L_{\mathrm{node}}
+\lambda_{\mathrm{stats}}\mathcal L_{\mathrm{stats}}
+\lambda_{\mathrm{impute}}\mathcal L_{\mathrm{impute}}
+\lambda_{\mathrm{scen}}\mathcal L_{\mathrm{scen}}
+\lambda_{\mathrm{smooth}}\mathcal L_{\mathrm{smooth}}.
\label{eq:loss-total}
\end{equation}
We tune $\{\lambda_{\cdot}\}$ on rolling validation windows; a robust starting choice is $\lambda_{\mathrm{edge}}=1$, $\lambda_{\mathrm{node}}=0.5$, $\lambda_{\mathrm{stats}}=0.2$, $\lambda_{\mathrm{impute}}=0.5$, $\lambda_{\mathrm{scen}}=0.5$, and $\lambda_{\mathrm{smooth}}\in[0.01,0.05]$.

\subsubsection{Optimizer and learning-rate schedule}
We optimize with AdamW and optionally apply sharpness-aware minimization (SAM) for improved generalization under regime shifts.

\paragraph{Base optimizer (AdamW).}
We use AdamW with $\beta_1=0.9$, $\beta_2\in\{0.95,0.999\}$, and weight decay (typically $10^{-2}$) applied to non-normalization weights.

\paragraph{SAM wrapper.}
When using SAM, we wrap AdamW with neighborhood size $\rho\in[0.02,0.1]$ (we use $\rho=0.05$ unless otherwise stated). SAM performs two forward-backward passes per step and empirically improves robustness to distribution shift.

\paragraph{Parameter groups.}
We use two learning-rate groups: (i) newly introduced parameters (adapters, fusion, temporal core, heads) with learning rate $\mathrm{lr}_{\mathrm{new}}\approx 3\times 10^{-4}$; and (ii) parameter-efficient backbone updates (e.g., LoRA/adapters inside pre-trained encoders) with a smaller learning rate $\mathrm{lr}_{\mathrm{backbone}}\in[5\times 10^{-5},10^{-4}]$.

\paragraph{Schedule and stabilization.}
We apply linear warmup over the first 5--10\% of training steps followed by cosine decay. We use gradient clipping (e.g., $\|\nabla\|_2\le 1$), mixed precision (bf16/fp16), and early stopping based on rolling-window validation loss.

